<img width="486" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0b0c657b-be53-4ec4-974e-0827f5d5d56e">

In this example, we can clearly see that Erdösz-Renyi Pagerank frequency distribution like “homogenius” and we can call it “Poisson” degree distribution(see can below). On the other hand, Barabasi-Albert Pagerank frequency histogram demonstrates us that contains some “bigger” values and the reason of that is “power-law” degree distribution. In this distribution type, includes few highly connected (hubs) and many sparsely connected vertices. Hubs are clearly see on the graph as higher Pagerank score.

As we said above, Barabasi-Albert graph has highly connected vertices as called “hubs”. It can be seen on the graph, the bigger yellow scatter points are represented these bigger Pagerank values and sparsely connected vertices.

On the left side, Erdosz-Renyi Pagerank scores are nearly same and similar(the reason of homogeneous). It has the Possion Distribution behaviour that called “expected similar values in the graph, also expected lower variance in Pagerank distribution).

***Comparasions.png***

We said before, lower variance expected in ER, because it’s degree distribution expected low in Poisson distribution.   
Other comparisons like coefficients, we can say: 

- Clustering coefficient gives us the vertices how interconnected with their neighbors. Therefore, in the previous plots we can clearly see in BA vertices are much more connected each other than ER. In the plot, hubs are connected with vertices and thats seems like “group” and “cluster”. It’s usually expected “high clustering coefficient” in small world networks.  
- Even though nodes may be relatively close to each other in ER, they are not likely to form tightly connected groups or clusters due to the random nature of connections.

**Edge Probability Calculation**  
<img width="455" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7f1c02be-8352-4c50-b777-3bd628dbad55">


*p \= probablity of the edge between two nodes*  
*The equation for the expected value in a binomial distribution is E(X) \= np, so N-1 is the possible number of the nodes except for one node itself.*

**Total Possible Edges**  
*\# Total possible edges in the graph, N\*(N-1))/2*  
Vertices that in the graph are connecting with n times non-directional edge as random way. So that, connections that among vertices were created with that selection.  

<img width="432" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c8434d9e-f536-48b3-a0bc-45df05ab14af">


**Expected Diameter**  
*\# The diameter of the Erdős-Rényi graph is approximately log2(N)*  
Diameter gives us the shortest way in the farthest two vertices in the Graph.  
If diameter is too low, that means vertices can linked easier.(in social graph, small diameter means that connections & knowledge able to spread quickly).  
Diameter is small especially in small world networks like include specs as BA)

<img width="440" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/325ed470-10b1-4db4-9693-18c7b09f837c">


*\# The diameter of the Barabási-Albert graph is approximately log2(N) / log2(log2(N))*      

<img width="460" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/45e90ca6-5209-40bc-a124-335d0eafa75d">


**Connection Parameter in the BA Graph**  
*\# Connection parameter needs for “number of edges to attach from a new node to existing nodes”*  
*\# The reason of dividing by 2 is that the Barabási-Albert model, each edge contributes to the degree of two nodes.*  

<img width="423" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c66ae067-61c2-4bd5-a002-ac1b3866f474">


**Clustering Coefficient**  
The clustering coefficient of the Erdős-Rényi graph is approximately 1 / N.   
Clustering coefficient gives us the vertices how interconnected with their neighbors. If any vertices are mostly connected with its neighbors, clustering coefficient are going to be high. This enables us to understand the concept of “clustering” and “groups” in the graph.

<img width="437" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/bcbd54d8-20cc-4a6a-81a3-9408c5ea0600">


*\# The clustering coefficient of the Barabási-Albert graph is approximately 1 / N^0.75*  

<img width="408" alt="image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2896a71a-6eef-4a48-8f53-ee4e693d8fd7">
